{"title_page": "Bottle sling", "text_new": "{{Knot-details\n| name=Bottle Sling (Scoutcraft Knot)\n| image=Jug-sling-wine-bottle-ABOK-1142.jpg\n| caption=\n| names=Bottle knot, Jug sling, Jug knot, Jar knot, Moonshiner's knot, Hackamore, Hackamore knot, Bridle knot, Beggarman's knot\n| type=binding\n| strength= \n| origin=Ancient\n| related=[[Jury mast knot]], [[Miller's knot]], [[Fiador knot]]\n| releasing= \n| uses=Suspending bottles and other similar objects\n| caveat=Cord must be scaled to size of bottle's flare or collar\n| abok_number=#260, '''#1142''', #2007, #2186, #2300, '''#2554'''\n}}\n\nThe '''bottle sling''' (or '''jug sling/ Scoutcraft Knot''') is a [[knot]] which can be used to create a handle for a glass or ceramic container with a slippery narrow neck, as long as the neck widens slightly near the top.<ref name=\"ashley208\">{{citation |last=Ashley |first=Clifford W. |title=The Ashley Book of Knots |url= |accessdate= |origyear= |year= 1944 |publisher=Doubleday |location=New York |isbn= |page=208}}</ref>\n\nWhile classed with [[List of binding knots|binding knots]], such as the [[reef knot]] and [[miller's knot]], the bottle sling is able to perform a function for which most other binding knots are unsuited.  The bottle sling's specific form allows it to grip a cylinder, assuming it has even a slight flare or collar, and lift it along its axis when the knot is loaded by all four strands.<ref name=\"ashley208\"/>  With appropriate size cord, most wine bottles can be reliably suspended with this knot.\n\n==History==\nThe bottle sling was described in detail by the [[Ancient Greek medicine|Greek physician]] [[Heraklas]] in his first century [[monograph]] on surgical knots and slings.  It was included under the name ''diplous karkhesios brokhos'' (\"double jug-sling noose\").  Clearly familiar with the knot, Heraklas provided three distinct tying methods.<ref name=\"quipus119\">{{citation |last=Day |first=Cyrus L. |title=Quipus and Witches' Knots |url= |accessdate= |origyear= |year= 1967 |publisher=University of Kansas Press |location=Lawrence |isbn= |pages= 87\u201388, 119\u2013124 |quote= }}</ref><ref name=\"hage652\">{{citation|last=Hage|first=J. Joris|periodical=World Journal of Surgery|date=April 2008|volume=32|title=Heraklas on Knots: Sixteen Surgical Nooses and Knots from the First Century A.D.|doi=10.1007/s00268-007-9359-x|pmid=18224483|issue=4|pages=648\u201355}}</ref>  Knot expert Cyrus L. Day believed the bottle sling was not described again in print until Craigin's 1884 ''A Boy's Workshop'',<ref name=\"quipus88\">Day(1967), p. 88</ref><ref name=\"Cragin\">{{Cite book|title=A Boy's Workshop|url=https://archive.org/details/aboysworkshopwi00cragoog|last=Craigin|first=Harry|year=1884|location=Boston|publisher=Lothrop, Lee & Shepard|pages=[https://archive.org/details/aboysworkshopwi00cragoog/page/n218 212]\u2013213}}</ref> although [[Clifford Ashley]] noted it was illustrated in Johann R\u00f6ding's 1795 ''Allgemeines W\u00f6rterbuch der Marine''.<ref name=\"ashley208\"/> More recently, the Bottle Sling has been nationally recognized by the [[Boy Scouts of America]] as the symbol of Outdoor Skills by scout camps throughout the country.\n\n==Usage==\n[[File:Fiador-mockup-with-Becket hitch-Fiador knot-and-Bottle sling.jpg|upright|right|thumb|Mockup of a rope [[fiador (tack)|fiador]] with the doubled \"hackamore knot\" at the bottom]]\nAs the name suggests, the primary use for this knot is to suspend bottles, jugs, and other items with similar shapes.  The space at the center of the knot is dropped over the top of a bottle or similar object.  Firmly pulling on all four ends emerging from the knot tightens it against the neck of the bottle.  Looping the running ends through the bight and tying them together will make a sling that grips and can be used to lift the bottle.<ref name=\"budcomp80\">{{Citation|first=Geoffrey|last=Budworth|title=The Complete Book of Knots|location=London|publisher=Octopus|year=1997|pages=80\u201381}}</ref>  This provides a convenient method of lowering a beverage bottle from a boat into the water to chill.\n\nAs mentioned above, the knot is believed to have been used medically in ancient Greece for applying [[Traction (orthopedics)|traction]] in the [[Reduction (orthopedic surgery)|reduction]] of [[Bone fracture|fracture]]s and [[Joint dislocation|dislocations]].  However it is not known to have any current medical application.<ref name=\"hage652\"/>\n\nThe knot is also said to have been used as an improvised emergency [[bridle]] when [[rope]] was the only material at hand.  Its use is described with the central parts of the knot acting as a [[Bit (horse)|bit]], one of the knot's outer [[Bight (knot)|bight]]s passing over the top of the animal's muzzle, and the other passing under the [[Mandible|jaw]] to form the [[noseband]].  The closed loop end of the knot would be placed over the animal's head and behind the ears, as a crownpiece, and the two free ends coming off under the chin used as [[rein]]s.  It was intended only for temporary use.<ref name=\"riley1912\">{{cite journal|last=Riley|first=Howard W.|author-link=Howard W. Riley|journal=The Cornell Reading-Courses|title=Knots, Hitches, and Splices|series=Rural Engineering Series No. 1|volume=1|issue=8|publisher=New York State College of Agriculture at Cornell University|location=Ithaca, NY|date=January 1912|page=1449|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bNNKAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA1449#v=onepage|accessdate=2011-11-08}} As collected in ''Documents of the Assembly of the State of New York'', 136th Session, 1913, Vol. 19, No. 29, Part 5.</ref>  However at least one author has disputed this as \"nonsense\" and suggests its only proper [[Equestrianism|equestrian]] use is in a doubled form, in this context known as a '''hackamore knot''', to secure the [[fiador (tack)|fiador]] to the [[bosal]] in some [[hackamore]] designs.<ref name=\"encybraid144\">{{Citation|first=Bruce|last=Grant|title=Encyclopedia of Rawhide and Leather Braiding|year=2004|origyear=1972|publisher=Cornell Maritime Press|location=Atglen, Pennsylvania|page=144}}</ref>\n\n==Tying==\nPerhaps not surprisingly\u2014given three were already known to the ancient Greeks\u2014there are many methods to tie the bottle sling.  Swedish physiologist and knot researcher Hjalmar \u00d6hrvall listed eight in his 1916 book ''Om Knutar''.<ref name=\"pvdg-hao-1\">{{Citation|last=van de Griend|first=Pieter|title=Hjalmar \u00d6hrwall on Knots (1): Life and Works|date=May 2008|journal=Knot News|publisher=International Guild of Knot Tyers - Pacific Branch|issn=1554-1843|issue=67}}</ref><ref name=\"omknutar\">{{Cite book|first=Hjalmar|last=\u00d6hrvall|title=Om Knutar''|edition=2nd|location=Stockholm|publisher=Albert Bonniers F\u00f6rlag|year=1916|pages=96\u2013104|url=http://runeberg.org/knutar/}}</ref>\n\nOne method for tying the bottle sling is similar to the loop-and-weave method used to tie the [[jury mast knot]] and the [[trumpet knot]].  The knot is begun by making a [[Bight (knot)|bight]] in a piece of rope and folding the bight back on itself to make two separated loops that are mirror images of each other.  Lay one loop on top of the other so that they overlap slightly and create a cat's eye shaped hole above a triangular shaped hole between the two loops.  Make a bird's beak with your index and thumb and weave them down through the loop, up through the cat's eye and down through the bottom loop, bunching the coils of rope against your fingers.  Pinch the section of rope that was the bottom of the triangle and flip the coils over the pinched section.  The flip may take a little practice, but the pinched section should become a short bight hanging off a circular shaped knot.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Bottle Sling ABOK 1142 Tying Step 1.jpg|Overlapping the loops\nFile:Bottle Sling ABOK 1142 Tying Step 2.jpg|Path the bight takes through the cat's eye\nFile:Bottle Sling ABOK 1142 Tying Step 3.jpg|Flipping the knot\nFile:Bottle Sling ABOK 1142 Tying Complete.jpg|Final configuration\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bottle cage]]\n* [[List of binding knots]]\n* [[List of knots]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fB9sum_GyxE Brief video of one tying method]\n* [http://www.enm.bris.ac.uk/staff/rrc/knots/axisbend.pdf Bottle sling discussed in relation to an alternative knot]\n* [https://gumroad.com/l/ArbIP cheap jar sling knot 3d model]\n\n{{Knots}}\n", "text_old": "{{Knot-details\n| name=Bottle Sling (Scoutcraft Knot)\n| image=Jug-sling-wine-bottle-ABOK-1142.jpg\n| caption=\n| names=Bottle knot, Jug sling, Jug knot, Jar knot, Moonshiner's knot, Hackamore, Hackamore knot, Bridle knot, Beggarman's knot\n| type=binding\n| strength= \n| origin=Ancient\n| related=[[Jury mast knot]], [[Miller's knot]], [[Fiador knot]]\n| releasing= \n| uses=Suspending bottles and other similar objects\n| caveat=Cord must be scaled to size of bottle's flare or collar\n| abok_number=#260, '''#1142''', #2007, #2186, #2300, '''#2554'''\n}}\n\nThe '''bottle sling''' (or '''jug sling/ Scoutcraft Knot''') is a [[knot]] which can be used to create a handle for a glass or ceramic container with a slippery narrow neck, as long as the neck widens slightly near the top.<ref name=\"ashley208\">{{citation |last=Ashley |first=Clifford W. |title=The Ashley Book of Knots |url= |accessdate= |origyear= |year= 1944 |publisher=Doubleday |location=New York |isbn= |page=208}}</ref>\n\nWhile classed with [[List of binding knots|binding knots]], such as the [[reef knot]] and [[miller's knot]], the bottle sling is able to perform a function for which most other binding knots are unsuited.  The bottle sling's specific form allows it to grip a cylinder, assuming it has even a slight flare or collar, and lift it along its axis when the knot is loaded by all four strands.<ref name=\"ashley208\"/>  With appropriate size cord, most wine bottles can be reliably suspended with this knot.\n\n==